BILINGUAL DRAMA SYNOPSIS
Write two synopses that would appear on a streaming platform to attract viewers.
Both must name characters using the CHARACTER REFERENCE table above:
  synopsis_zh — use the Chinese names (left side of →)
  synopsis_en — use the Westernized English names (right side of →)

Rules for synopsis_zh (中文简介):
  • 250–400 Chinese characters
  • Opens with a hook that drops the viewer into the central conflict immediately
  • Names the protagonist and the core causal threat in the first two sentences
  • Ends on an unresolved tension that makes the reader want to watch
  • Prose style: crisp, commercial short-drama copy — not academic summary

Rules for synopsis_en (English synopsis):
  • 120–200 words
  • Same narrative arc as synopsis_zh — translated in spirit, not word-for-word
  • Uses Westernized character names consistently; if a character has no canonical_en
    name in the reference table, romanize the Chinese name (Pinyin, Title Case)
  • Suitable for an English-language streaming platform description field
  • Ends with the same unresolved hook as the Chinese version

ABSOLUTE PROHIBITION (applies to all fields):
  ✗ No percentages, numeric scores, intensity ratings, or saturation levels
  ✗ No phrases like "crisis level", "dramatic weight", "tension degree"
  ✗ No subjective adjectives quantifying emotion (e.g. "highly emotional")
  ✗ State structural, causal, factual observations only (except in the synopsis fields,
    where engaging prose is required — but still no numeric intensity ratings)

